1 Flights

As we just mentioned before, Markdown was originally designed for HTML output, so it may not be surprising that the HTML format has the richest features among all output formats. We recommend that you read this full section before you learn other output formats, because other formats have several features in common with the HTML document format, and we will not repeat these features in the corresponding sections.

perf <- flights %>% group_by(carrier) %>% summarize(total=n(),delayed=sum(dep_delay>0,na.rm = TRUE),canceled=sum(is.na(dep_delay))) %>% mutate(on_time=total-delayed-canceled)

perf

4 U.S. Elections

If you are not familiar with R Markdown, we recommend that you read at least Chapter 2 to learn the basics. All the rest of the chapters in this book can be read in any order you desire. They are pretty much orthogonal to each other.

elections <- elections_historic %>% mutate(century=as.character(1+year%/%100))
ggplot(elections,aes(popular_pct,ec_pct))+
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0.5,color="grey")+
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0.5,color="grey")+
  geom_point(aes(color=century))+
  geom_text_repel(aes(label=winner),size=2,seed=1)

ggplot()+
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0.5,color="grey")+
  geom_vline(xintercept = 0.5,color="grey")+
  geom_point(elections,mapping=aes(popular_pct,ec_pct,color=century))+
  geom_text_repel(filter(elections,winner %in% c("Donald Trump","Barack Obama")),mapping=aes(popular_pct,ec_pct,label=winner),seed=1)
